03879nam a22005055i 9780773570085DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20022002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735700857 a10.1515/97807735700852doi  a(DE-B1597)657595  a(OCoLC)123470237  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9199.3.H59bZ74 2002eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a813/.541 aKeith, W.J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCanadian Odyssey :bA Reading of Hugh Hood's The New Age/Le nouveau siècle /cW.J. Keith. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (218 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroductory: Reading Hugh Hood -- tThe Mythos of Canadian Life -- tThe Making of The New Age -- tRoman-Fleuve -- tHood and His Precursors -- tTowards the New Age -- tThe Swing in the Garden -- tA New Athens -- tReservoir Ravine -- tBlack and White Keys -- tThe Scenic Art -- tThe Motor Boys in Ottawa -- tTony’s Book -- tProperty and Value -- tBe Sure to Close Your Eyes -- tDead Men’s Watches -- tGreat Realizations -- tNear Water -- tConclusion: Rereading Hugh Hood -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPublished between 1975 and 2000 and completed shortly before his death, Hugh Hood's twelve-volume novel-series The New Age/Le nouveau siècle represents a major achievement in Canadian fiction. Hood takes us on a remarkable, though challenging, journey in time and space while chronicling the life of his intellectually inquisitive protagonist, Matt Goderich. Moving from history and politics to literature and the arts, from popular song to the vagaries of fashion, from urban stress to the relaxations of cottage-country, these novels explore the texture of Canadian life with a depth and comprehensiveness that, when fully grasped, are dazzling. In Canadian Odyssey W.J. Keith steers general readers and specialist students alike through the complexities of Hood's scheme. He presents biographical information about the planning and writing of the series, places it among other examples of "Roman-Fleuve," offers background concerning Hood's literary influences, and provides novel-by-novel discussions of each book. Written in a straightforward style, avoiding jargon and the excesses of literary theory, Canadian Odyssey makes a convincing case for The New Age as a great Canadian masterpiece.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357008540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773570085423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773570085/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles